AGI -&nbsp;After attacks on politicians belonging to the ruling coalition in Germany, yesterday's violent attack which severely wounded Slovak Prime Minister Robert Fico raises concern for "the growth of episodes of violence that are manifesting in some European countries". To feed them, according to an analysis of Ispi, is the excessive polarization of national political systems. As the vice president of the institute writes in a comment, Antonio Villafranca, "it is indicative that these episodes also occur in Germany - where various political representatives have been attacked in recent weeks. In an international context, with two wars at its doors, Europe must maintain its democratic space and reject all forms of extremism," according to the expert.
<br> Ispi recalls that Fico is "considered the Viktor Orban of Slovakia", and that it governs a populist and Eurosceptic executive thanks to a coalition with the Hlas-Sd of Peter Pellegrini, recently elected president, and the extreme right of the Slovak National Party. "In a blatant break with the policy pursued by his predecessor, Eduard Heger, he detained Bratislava on anti-Ukraine positions by accusing Brussels and Western allies of having "prolonged the conflict" with support to Kiev against the invasion of Moscow and having "damaged the EU more than Russia".
<br Its position was further strengthened in April, with the victory of Pellegrini in the presidential elections, which fueled fears on the rule of law and the possible deviation of the country from the common policy on support for Ukraine and NATO.
&nbsp;
Fico had already been Prime Minister of Slovakia for over a decade, between 2006 and 2010 and then again from 2012 to 2018. He was then forced to resign in March of that year after weeks of mass protests for the murder of investigative journalist Jan Kuciak and his fiancée, Martina Kunirova.
<br The brutal attack of yesterday, writes the Ispi, "is matured in a context of increasing tension that crosses Slovakia. Milan Nic, former adviser to the Slovak Deputy Foreign Minister, declared that the political system in the country has been polarized for several years, and that the one in Fico "is not an isolated incident". Before today, in fact, he underlined Nic "other politicians were threatened", including the outgoing president Zuzana Caputova, centrist and Europeanist, who decided not to apply for re-election after receiving death threats, declaring "exhaust" of the political atmosphere in the country. Yesterday he called the attack against his political opponent a " brutal and ruthless attack on democracy" and added: "The police arrested the offender and will provide more information when possible. Until then, we don't give fast judgments, please. I think the most important thing we should all focus on right now is the quick recovery of Robert Fico."
&nbsp;
A reference, it seems, to the words of the deputy speaker of Parliament, Lubos Blaha, who once learned of the attack turned towards the opposition benches saying: "It's your fault." In these days the parliament is struggling with a controversial bill that would revoke the public service RTVS and establish a new broadcaster more favorable to the government, according to critics. An anti-government protest scheduled for this evening in Bratislava was revoked after the assault on premier.&nbsp;

