AGI -&nbsp; "Today we open a formal Dsa investigation against Meta. We are not convinced that Meta has done enough to comply with Dsa obligations to mitigate the risks of negative effects on the physical and mental health of young Europeans on its Facebook and Instagram platforms." He announced on X the European Commissioner at the Internal Market, Thierry Breton.
&nbsp;
In detail, the survey concerns Meta's compliance with Dsa's obligations on assessing and mitigating risks caused by the design of online interfaces of Facebook and Instagram, which could exploit weak points and inexperience of minors and cause dependence behaviour, and/or strengthen the so-called "black rabbit" effect. The evaluation - the Commission explains - is necessary to counter the potential risks for the exercise of the fundamental right to the physical and mental well-being of minors and to respect their rights.<br> Moreover, Meta's compliance with the Dsa requirements in relation to mitigation measures to prevent access by minors to inappropriate content, in particular instruments of verification of the age used by Meta, which may not be reasonable, proportionate and effective.
<br> Finally, Meta's compliance with Dsa obligations is examined to implement appropriate and proportionate measures to ensure a high level of privacy, security and protection for minors, in particular with regard to the default privacy settings for minors as part of the design and operation of their recommendation systems. &nbsp;

