AGI -&nbsp; California State University has left the president of the state campus of Sonoma, Mike Lee, who had accepted the demands of the protesters to be involved in the university decision-making process and to exclude Israel from the partnerships with the athenaeologist.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
On Tuesday, Lee sent a note to the entire campus where he had made several concessions to the occupants of a pro-Palestinian camp. The note was sent "without the appropriate approvals," announced with a note the chancellor of CSU Mildred Garcia, adding that she and the advice of the 23 campuses are "examined the issue", writes Politico.
&nbsp;
"For now, because of this insubordination and the consequences that led to the system, President Lee was put on administrative leave," said Garciia.<br> The punishment perhaps marks the toughest disciplinary action against a rector or president of a campus in California for the management of protests against the war in Gaza. It also underlines the reluctance to disinvest Israeli weapons producers - as pro-Palestinian protesters throughout the country have increasingly asked in recent months - by leaders of the CSU system and the twin system of the University of California.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp; The universities of California, including the UC Riverside, the UC Berkeley and the Sacramento State, agreed to take into consideration the disinvestment and so did some universities on the eastern coast, but no one arrived until Lee's initiatives.
&nbsp;
The academic boycott of Israel decided by the President of the State campus of Sonoma provided, among other things, that the study proposals in Israel would be removed from university pamphlets. Lee has also agreed to work with a local section of the group of activists 'Students for Justice in Palestinà to form an advisory council on some decisions.<br> Lee also pledged to review school contracts and a specific investment fund for the campus called Sonoma State Foundation for links with Israel "to determine an action line that leads to disinvestment strategies that include the search for ethical alternatives."
<br "In my attempt to reach an agreement with a group of students, I marginalized other members of our student population and community," Lee wrote in a follow-up message to campus members Wednesday. "I realize the damage it caused and I take full responsibility. I deeply regret the unintentional consequences of my actions." &nbsp;

